english:
  title: Record of the Clear Feast Pavilion
  author: Kim Yeon
  language: eng
  text: "The King, possessed of brilliance and profundity, of integrity and radiant virtue, reveres the Way of the Sages and cherishes the culture of the Middle Kingdom. Thus, beside the great palace, between the Hall of Welcoming Texts to the north and the Hall of Compassion to the south, he established two pavilions—the Precious Script Pavilion and the Clear Feast Pavilion.\n\nIn one, he placed the imperial edicts, calligraphy, and paintings of the Song emperor, that they might serve as models of instruction. Before viewing them, one must bow with reverent composure. In the other, he gathered the writings of all ages from Zhou Gong and Confucius through Mencius and Yang Xiong—a treasury of wisdom. There, with learned elders and accomplished scholars, he daily discusses and illuminates the Way of the Ancient Kings. Within this single hall, the teachings of the Three Bonds and Five Relationships, the principles of human nature, destiny, and virtue, saturate the very air.\n\nThen came the fourth month of summer in the Year of the Fire Rooster, on the second day of the Jiaxu cycle. The King summoned his highest officials—the Grand Protector Minister, the Minister of State, the Guardian Minister, the Commandant of the Secret Council, and all the great officers of court—and held a grand feast at the Clear Feast Pavilion.\n\nThere, the King spoke at leisure: \"Though my virtue is unworthy, Heaven has granted us peace. The altars of state flourish. War has ceased at the borders, and our culture aligns with that of the Middle Kingdom. In all matters of governance, large and small, I rely upon your counsel. Following the precedents of the Chongning and Daguang eras, I have established this library to seek out the learned and wise, and this hall to receive my ministers in intimate counsel—patterns drawn from the great houses of old. Though the ceremonies differ in grandeur, the aim to honor the worthy and esteem the capable remains the same.\n\nToday, our emissary returns from the Song court bearing tribute—rare spices, imperial wine, precious tea, exotic fruits, and fine vessels. I wish to celebrate this fortune with you.\"\n\nThe officials, overwhelmed with gratitude, bowed low and demurred. But the King urged them to be seated, welcomed them with warm countenance, and caused every delicacy to be served. The precious treasures of the Six Departments and the finest foods of the four quarters were laid out in abundance—glass, agate, jade, and wonders from afar arranged upon the tables. From the hall below rose harmonious music: the dulcet tones of pipes and flutes, the melodies of zither and bell, sounds both refined and noble.\n\nThe King raised his cup and commanded his ministers to drink freely: \"Between ruler and subject, nothing matters but sincerity. Drink without restraint.\" \n\nThe cups circled nine times. As the feast deepened, the King had robes and belts bestowed upon his guests. He then bade them rise and be at ease. Some spoke and laughed openly, others wandered to admire the gardens. Beyond the pavilion's rails, stones had been arranged into mountains; water had been drawn into pools. In multiform splendor, the crystal waters reflected back the beauty of distant lakes and southern vistas.\n\nThe night deepened. At last, satiated and merry, they departed.\n\nAfterward, the officials spoke among themselves in wonder: \"Our King embodies frugality, yet knows no excess. He wears no silk, uses no carved ornaments. Daily he labors over the welfare of his people, yet when entertaining his ministers and honored guests, he opens the imperial treasury without hesitation, burns candles long into the night, and counts it no extravagance. His reverence for the worthy, his respect for propriety, his love of virtue—truly these exceed the wisdom of a hundred kings.\"\n\nI have read that in ancient times, the Duke of Lu used the rites and music of Heaven to transform his people. At the Grand Hall, the learned and wise took joy together, as the poem tells: \"The ruler of Lu arrives at the hall of learning, and drinks of fine wine. Having tasted these excellent spirits, may he never know age.\" In the palace, ministers and officials alike partook of his generosity, and the poem proclaims: \"The ruler of Lu feasts in gladness; his ministers and people share in his joy. The state prospers; abundant blessings fall upon us all.\"\n\nNow our King, receiving the grace of the Son of Heaven, honors his servants with this same benevolence. His ministers, moved by his virtue, respond in kind. The musicians compose songs of mutual delight between ruler and subject. In this moment of shared joy and proper ceremony, the harmony of heaven and earth, the communion of high and low, the transformation of customs—all flow forth from this fellowship of eating and drinking, of laughter and contemplation.\n\nIs it not so that from such moments spring the blessings of ten thousand years? That peace eternal may answer the boundless grace of the Son of Heaven?\n\nI, though unworthy and lacking in talent, have been granted this unexpected fortune and entrusted with office. Commanded to set down this record, I cannot refuse. Therefore, I bow and humbly submit this account."
  footnotes:
    - The Three Bonds refer to the hierarchical relationships between ruler and subject, father and son, and husband and wife. The Five Relationships add those between elder and younger brother, and between friends.
    - The Six Departments (Liu Shang) refers to the six ministries of the imperial government.
    - The poems referenced are from the Classic of Poetry (Shijing), reflecting on royal virtue and the proper ordering of the state.
